In California, people can get extra money if the other person acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Malice means acting with bad intention or doing something very bad on purpose. The law says that if someone is very careful and still does something wrong, it can be considered malice. A court has said that someone acts with malice if they know something bad will happen and they do nothing to stop it.

I learned about Islam four years ago in a class at CBC.  The main topic of discussion was whether Islam is a hostile religion.  Now, the question is more important than ever.  I look back at what happened after 9/11.  The media had a bad view of Islam and its extreme followers.  But now, they show a lot of respect for Islam in America.  I do not think it is possible for America to elect a president like Barack Obama, who has Muslim family background, in 2001.

The story of the Prophet Muhammad is interesting to me.  What I know of his history does not match his personality.  From what I learned, Muhammad forced people to be Muslims.  He conquered tribes and made them be Muslim.  But his biography says he was a humble and kind person.  People came to him because they believed in his teachings.

I see some similarities between the work of Jesus and the miracles of Muhammad.  One example is when Muhammad had some food and drink, and it was enough for many people.  The way this story is written makes me think the writers wanted people to see Muhammad as a kind and humble man who did not need to prove anything.  This makes me think they are not telling the truth about Jesus.

There are many stories in the biography that make it seem like people wanted to prove that Muhammad was a special person.  But some of these stories come from people who heard from others.  I did not like this because it makes the stories seem less true.

I am concerned that the writers try to make Muhammad a good person.  But history says he was not a kind and humble man.  I wonder if Muslims know the real story of how Muhammad became powerful.

Jesus' teachings were not part of Christian thought after his death. Instead, they moved away from his ideas. If we look at history, we see a pattern of Christianity moving farther from its start. Today, there is a growing movement to know more about Jesus and his ideas.  More people will study the history of Christianity and understand the true teachings of Jesus. They will try to separate the ideas that were added to Christianity over time from the original teachings of Jesus. It may take time, but eventually, people will go back to the original ideas. A movement will grow and remove the added ideas, one by one. This will be like moving the clock backward. When this happens, the church will be the leader. People will follow only Jesus' ideas, not the ideas added later. The church will be strong, but people will have more uniform ideas. They will be more alike instead of different. 

History shows us that things can change. For example, Christians were once persecuted. But later, the Roman Empire became Christian. Our country also improved from slavery to freedom. The same thing will happen to Christianity. People will go back to the teachings of Jesus. 

It is also important to understand Jesus' words as metaphors, not as direct statements. This will help people move forward. If we look back in history, we see only the Jewish religion. The Jewish people divided into groups like Sadducees, Pharisees, and others. They had different ideas about God and the scriptures.

The book The Jungle shows that human beings are naturally selfish. They want to improve their lives, but they do not care about others. The Jungle shows this in many ways. One example is the factory owners and managers. They want to make their factories big and successful. They do not care about people or animals that get hurt because of their actions.

According to the author, Upton Sinclair, the factories are very damaging to the environment. He writes, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky..." This shows the damage the factories are causing. The owners do not care about the smoke and pollution they create or the dirty water that comes from the animal pens.

The factory owners and managers also do not care about their workers. They want to make money, so they work their employees hard and without pay. They can lay off workers at any time. The workers had no protection during that time. The owners and managers were in control, and the workers were like slaves. The workers were poor and had no way to get help. Some workers even formed unions, but these groups often took money from the workers.

The Jungle shows that people are selfish and do not care about others. The book says that when people are treated very badly, they will act badly too. This is like the old system of slavery.

Many authors use special writing methods to make readers feel a certain way about important subjects. 
Some methods are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many of these methods in his book The Great Gatsby. He uses words in special ways to make readers feel a certain way. For example, he pairs a color with a noun that do not usually go together. He uses many colors, including gold, green, white, gray, red, and pink.

In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald gives special meanings to some colors. He uses white and gray to make readers feel a certain way about important things. He uses these colors in the beginning of the book to show that they are important. People in the book, like Daisy and Jordan, often wear white. They wear white clothes and look nice and clean. Fitzgerald uses colors like this in other parts of the book too. For example, he says that some people are "gray" and that some things are "white." He uses these words to show that these people and things are not exciting or special.

Fitzgerald uses these colors to make readers think about the people and things in a certain way. He wants readers to see some people and things as boring or less important. For example, Fitzgerald does not use the colors white and gray for a long time, and then he describes Daisy as wearing white again. This makes readers see her as not special or interesting. He uses this method again to make readers see her as just a person that Gatsby wants.

Fitzgerald uses the colors white and gray to make readers feel a certain way about some people and things in his book. He wants readers to think about them in a certain way.

San Diego County is a good place for growing many foods. The climate is mild and sunny. People grow many crops there, including tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, and fruits like peaches and lemons. They also grow berries, honey, and peppers. Many people want to buy organic food from local farms. These farms have long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular.

Some organic farms in San Diego give tours and let people walk on the land and watch birds. This is good for people who like nature. It helps the landowner and makes money for the farm. 

But organic farming is more expensive than regular farming. It needs more work to kill pests and weeds and to make the soil healthy without using chemicals. The farm may lose more food. Small organic farms are not as efficient as big farms. They have to do more work to protect the environment.

The land in this example is in a place called Potrero, near a national forest. It is 160 acres of land with different types of plants and trees. Many plants and animals live there that are in danger. The government is working on a plan to protect them.

For a long time, people lived on this land. They were Native Americans and then cattle ranchers and wood sellers. The land was probably used for grazing and cutting wood.

I looked at a real estate website and found a farm in the same area. I learned about government programs that can help small farmers save money and protect the environment. This was a way for me to show what a farmer in this area might do.

Culture is very important in any kind of negotiation. It is hard to define culture. Culture is not the same in all places. It is not just one thing. We should not say all people from a certain country are the same. For example, it is not true that all Russians are stubborn or all Japanese are accommodating. When we meet people from another culture, we can understand it better by comparing it to our own culture.

To know a foreign culture, we can learn about its history, its values, and its problems. We should not judge or try to change a culture. We should accept it as it is. This is especially true when we are in a weaker position in a negotiation. If we respect a culture, we can overcome any problems and move forward.

Culture is not just about countries. Companies also have their own culture. Some companies work very hard, while others have a more relaxed schedule. We can see a company's culture in the way its employees dress, the way they communicate, and the way they hire people. Even in America, different companies have different cultures, and there is a lot of diversity in corporate culture.

Understanding values is very important. Values tell us why a culture does things in a certain way. If a culture values saving face or harmony, a negotiator will not shame his company or his boss. If a culture values a hard bargain, a negotiator will not settle quickly. We should think about these things before we negotiate. But it is also good to learn about the other person's personality and values to be a good negotiator.

There is an old saying: "The fool says in his heart, 'There is no God.'" This quote is from the Bible and is also used by the famous thinker Thomas Aquinas. Both thinkers write about the same thing - the existence of God. We will compare their ideas. But first, we must assume that they are both right. If we don't, we cannot compare their ideas. What if they believed in a different kind of God? We will look at the idea of the God in the Bible.

Let's start with St. Anselm. He says that we can know God exists by thinking about it. We can understand God by looking inside ourselves. He says that we cannot think about God not existing. This means that God exists in our minds. Anselm does not need outside evidence to prove God's existence. He believes that faith is enough. This idea is important in Christianity because it means that people can believe in God without proof.

Thomas Aquinas has a different idea. He thinks that we can prove God exists using logic and evidence. He does not need faith. This idea is good for spreading Christianity because people can be convinced by reason, not just faith. Aquinas writes about five reasons why God exists: change, cause and effect, things that depend on others, degrees of good and bad, and harmony. He says that these reasons show that God is necessary. If you are missing a piece of a puzzle, you can know what it looks like and that it exists without seeing it.

A long time ago, in the fifth or sixth century, a prince was born. This man would one day be known as Buddha. He lived a long time and became a wise man. He gave up the world and found the answer to life. His teachings formed a new religion called Buddhism. This religion is over 2,500 years old.

Buddhism is different now from what it was when Buddha was alive. This can be seen in Sri Lanka, a country where Theravada Buddhism is the main religion. In this country, a special ceremony happens every year. People cut water to mark the start of a special time. Monks and lay people do this together. This ceremony is important, but Buddha never taught about it.

Buddhism has changed in many ways. This is true from the simple rules to the deeper meaning of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community has changed its rules over time. This is true for both monks and lay people. This change came from both inside and outside the community.

We need to know some words to talk about the changes in Buddhism. An "internal force" is a change that comes from inside the Buddhist community. An "external force" is a change that comes from outside the community. A "hostile force" is a change that hurts the Buddhist community. A "benign force" is a change that does not hurt the community, but it could have bad effects.

Now, we need to look at the basics of Buddhism. Buddhists go to the triple gem for help. The triple gem is the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is the Buddhist text, which is divided into three parts. The Sutta Pitaka has the teachings of Buddha. The Vinaya Pitaka has the rules for living. The Abhidhamma Pitaka has the deeper meaning of Buddhism. These deeper meanings include no soul (Anatta), suffering (Dukkha), and everything changes (Anicca). If we understand these ideas, we can stop the cycle of death and rebirth, called Sansara. Sansara is a never-ending cycle of suffering, desire, hatred, and ignorance. When we become wise, we can leave this cycle behind. In the Vinaya Pitaka, there are rules for monks and lay people to follow. For lay people, there are five simple rules: do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not be immoral, and do not take too much drink. For monks, there are many more rules. The main idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. First, life is suffering. Second, attachment causes suffering. Third, suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico were once two countries with a long history of disagreement. This disagreement lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The United States and Mexico fought a war from 1846 to 1848. The US won the war and took control of Texas and parts of the American Southwest.

There were many other times when the two countries disagreed. But their disagreements started to decrease before World War One. The United States and Mexico disagreed over things like religion, culture, and traditions. They also disagreed over things like money and land.

This is not new. Many countries with shared borders disagree with each other. They often disagree over things like land and money. The US and Mexico are not the only countries with a long history of disagreement. Cuba is another country that has had many problems with the US.

The two countries were also divided by their beliefs about God. This created a problem between them. Many countries have had problems because of disagreements about God. In the past, the US was against Catholicism and a king. Now, the US is against things like fascism and communism.

The US and Mexico did not get along because of the way the English and Spanish treated them in the past. The English and Spanish had a lot of disagreements, and the US and Mexico inherited these feelings. This made it hard for the two countries to be friends.

There were 17 times when the US and Mexico disagreed between 1836 and 1893. Most of these disagreements were about land and border problems. Bandits and outlaws from the US would cross the border and cause problems in Mexico. But the situation started to improve when Mexico became dependent on the US. The US then started to help Mexico with its economy instead of trying to take its land.

Fifteen years ago, I became sick with an illness I never knew about. I was a nurse at that time. I chose to be a nurse for a safe and secure life. I wanted a safe life because I did not have one as a child. People told me, "You will always find work. People will always get sick." I wanted to be a scientist or a journalist, but I chose nursing instead.

Now, I am 46 years old. I have no money, and I am not able to work. I get help from Social Security. But it is hard. Every day is a struggle. I have to ask for help from my family and friends. They have been very kind to me.

My point is that bad things can happen in life. There is no guarantee that everything will go well. We all need help sometimes.

I agree that the government is not perfect. We should not count on the government to help us all the time. But instead of just depending on the government, I think Americans should help each other. We should trust each other and share what we have.

Some people say that America was built on individualism. But that is not true. Our ancestors helped each other when they were in trouble. They shared their food and their homes. They moved together in groups to the West.

So, be prepared for bad times. I have a kit with supplies like water, food, and a first aid kit. I also have a plan for a safe house. But the most important thing is to know your neighbors. Talk to them and help them when they need it.

We want to know why living things change over time. Are there limits that affect how they change? In 1917, scientist D'Arcy Thompson said that it is difficult to explain the shape of living things in simple terms. But now, scientists are using math to study how some living things change over time. Our study is looking at how math can help us understand how living things change. We are studying a type of shellfish called Prunum. We are using math to help us understand how its shell changes.

We used special X-ray pictures to study the shapes of Prunum shells. We used these pictures to create math models. These models showed us what the shells might look like if they had changed in different ways. We are combining this math with experiments to learn more about how shells change over time.

A shell is like a tube that grows over time. It grows in a spiral shape, with each part of the spiral called a whorl. The whorls are connected by a line called a suture. The last whorl, or body whorl, is the biggest part of the shell. The other parts are called the spire. The tip of the spire is called the apex, and the other end is called the base. The animal comes out of its shell through a hole called the aperture.

We can look at shells in different ways. We can look at the top, the bottom, or the front or back of the shell. The usual way to look at a shell is from the front, with the hole facing us and the tip pointing up.

To count the whorls, we look at the shell from the top. We draw a line where the first suture starts. Then we count the whorls from that line. We can count to a quarter of a whorl if we need to.

A shell is like a path through time and space. It grows as the animal gets bigger. We can follow the path of the hole in the shell by looking at the center of each whorl and the size of the hole. We can use math to draw a picture of this path. This helps us understand how the animal's shell changes over time. We can use math to change the shell's shape and see what happens.

For ten years, the number of newborn and baby deaths in Indonesia has not changed much.  The country is making progress in many areas, such as building clean water systems and improving sanitation.  But it is not making enough progress in taking care of mothers and babies.

There are several reasons for this.  One reason is that many women still give birth at home without a doctor or nurse present.  This can be very bad if there are problems during delivery.  Another reason is that many children with diarrhea are not getting the care they need.  We also do not have good information about how well new mothers are being taken care of after giving birth.

Only 4% of births in Indonesia are cesarean sections, which is a lower number than it should be.  The number of cesarean sections is higher in cities than in rural areas.  This means that people in rural areas are not getting the same level of healthcare as people in cities.  Another problem is that the rich have better access to healthcare than the poor.  This is because the poor have to pay out of their own pockets for medical care.

To fix these problems, we need to think about how to get more healthcare services to people who need them.  One way to do this is to focus on one area of healthcare at a time.  This can lead to quick results and easy-to-measure goals.  But there are some problems with this approach.  For example, if we put too much money and resources into one area, we may not have enough for other areas.  This can make it hard for people who work in healthcare to get the support they need.

We also need to consider the fact that running many programs at the same time can cause problems.  It can lead to unnecessary paperwork and make it hard to coordinate between programs.  This can make it hard to get the help that people need.

Victorian novels are known for their detailed descriptions and focus on the aristocracy of that time. Two novels that are different from this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. These novels use mystery and strange situations to make the characters more real and interesting. This helps readers understand their feelings and reasons for acting in certain ways.

In these novels, mystery is often shown through dream-like scenes or confusing situations. In Oliver Twist, these strange events help readers understand Oliver's feelings and what he is experiencing. 

In one part of the book, Oliver has a dream or is in a dream-like state. He sees and hears things that did not really happen. It is like he is walking between two men who are arguing. The sounds of guns and loud voices make him feel pain and confuse him. He feels an unknown pain that does not go away. This shows that Oliver feels helpless and scared.

In another part of the book, Oliver has a nightmare about being shot. He remembers it like it was real. Even though he is in pain, he does not try to control the situation. He is not in charge of what is happening to him. This shows that Oliver feels defeated and does not know what to do.

In another novel, the day passes quickly. The night is very long and quiet, but it seems to end quickly. The author uses this to show the main character's feelings of sadness and confusion.

I worked with students at an after-school program two years ago. I helped them with their school work, especially in English and reading. One boy, Adrian, had trouble reading. He spoke English well, but some letters were hard for him to read. I thought it was strange. We worked together, but then I met his mother. She did not speak English, only Spanish. We used simple words and gestures to talk. I then understood the problem: Adrian knew how to read, but not the English alphabet.

I tell this story to show that a language barrier can be a big problem in school, especially in California. Even if a child speaks good English, reading can still be hard. I think we can all agree that this is a problem. So, what can we do? In Adrian's case, tutoring in English reading helped. But for children who do not speak much English, the solution is not simple.

We need a combination of things to solve this problem. Some people suggest a dual language system. This means teaching in two languages at the same time. We have found that children who learn in two languages do better in school. Some people are afraid that this idea is expensive and will not help most children. But this is not true. If we use this system more often, all children can benefit. But how can we do this? Do we need all teachers to speak two languages? No, this is not possible and not necessary. We can have extra help, like tutors or aids, who speak two languages.

From a young age, people are told that something big is out there. We are bigger than we can understand. Some people go to school to learn about it. Others think about it themselves. Many people believe in the religions their parents tell them about. But some people do not believe. They think there is nothing beyond what they see and feel. People change their minds and think about other things. We all search for our own ideas about spirituality. We want to find a way to understand the world.

I asked my father about his favorite bird. We sat on the front porch of our house. It was raining. We smoked cigarettes. He looked out into the rain. He seemed to be thinking about something. He was thin and sick. I wanted to talk to him, but I was afraid. I knew that talking about it would make it real.

My father died in December when I turned 22. He got treatment to stop his sickness, but it did not work. He was in a hospital for a few more months. I did not want to watch him die. I wanted to remember how he lived, not how he died. I knew my father better than anyone. I knew he would not have wanted me to watch him die. I stayed in my bed for three days. I waited for news.

No one called me.

The Gothic Novel is a mix of old and new ideas. This is what Ian Watt calls an "oxymoron," or a word that is a contradiction. The Gothic style has been both praised and criticized. Some people say it has no real depth, but others think it is a powerful way to express the "terrible sublime."

The first Gothic Novel was written by Horace Walpole. It is called The Castle of Otranto. This book combined old and new ideas from romance stories. Walpole used old theatrical elements and new ways of writing to create a new kind of story. He called it "A Gothic Story."

The Gothic style uses ideas from medieval times, like Gothic architecture and theater. Even when The Castle of Otranto was first published, the word "Gothic" was not used just to describe this style. It was used to describe many people, styles, and time periods. People thought it was old-fashioned and not modern.

The combination of old and new ideas in Gothic Novels is what makes them special. This is why they remain popular for a long time.

One important idea in Gothic Novels is the concept of chivalry. This idea is from medieval times. It is about the code of behavior for knights. In the first Gothic Novel, The Castle of Otranto, chivalry is used in a special way. The writer, Horace Walpole, wanted to show that society had lost its chivalrous values. He was writing during a time of great trouble in politics. He thought that the old values of chivalry were better than the morals of his time.

The character of Frederic in The Castle of Otranto is an example of this idea. He is a prince who has suffered a great loss. He is described as brave, courteous, and noble. These are all qualities of a chivalrous knight. Walpole uses these qualities to show what is missing in his society.

The Gothic style has been around for a long time. It is a mix of old and new ideas that continues to be popular today.

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from the customer to the final product. It includes the stages of raw materials, supply, production, and distribution. The term supply chain management was created in 1982 by a man named Keith Oliver. He described the process of planning, controlling, and organizing the supply chain to meet customer needs quickly and efficiently.

There are six main parts of a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these parts to give good service to customers.

Production is the first step in the supply chain. It is the base of the whole process. Managers decide what products to make and how many to make. They look at the market to see what customers want. The market helps them decide what products to make and how many.

Once managers decide what to make, they choose where to make it. They think about the quality and amount of products. They also think about customer needs. Then, they plan the work and take care of the equipment.

Production is an important step. Every detail is important. If one detail is not planned right, it can cost the company time and money. For example, companies like Wal-Mart and Target have a plan for every part of their business. They show how things should be done, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments. This helps the company work smoothly.

The second important part of the supply chain is supply. Supply means the company decides how to make things and who to work with. Companies may have many groups that make the same product. They decide which group is best for each part of the process. They may also work with other companies to make things. This helps the company be fast and flexible, and also saves money.

A sign in Burma says Hitler is alive. Ellen Page, an actress, stands alone on a street corner with a piece of paper above her head. The sign has a bad message. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a country in Southeast Asia. A bad government controls Burma. In 1962, the government took power by force. In 2007, people in the street began to protest. Many monks led the protests. The protests were named the Saffron Revolution because of the color of the monks' robes. The government at first allowed the monks to gather, but soon the situation became very bad. The military attacked the monks and many monasteries. Journalists were arrested and some were killed. The government said only 13 people died, but a former soldier said many more died.

This is not new. Many governments have tried to stop people from disagreeing with them throughout history. In ancient times, Roman leaders said they were chosen by gods to rule. Some people believe that Japanese leaders are gods. The current U.S. president, George Bush, has meetings with a man who leads a group that does not like certain people.

One bad example is the Tiananmen Square protest in China in 1989. Many students, workers, and intellectuals protested against the government. The government said 200-300 people died, but others said between 2,000-3,000 people died. Another bad thing happened in Rwanda in the 1990s. Hutu groups and the government killed many people who were not like them. The Nazis, led by Hitler, also killed many people who were Jewish.

Duke Ellington made a big impact on jazz music. He was a great composer and pianist who worked with his band for a long time. He was able to make each musician in the band sound good on their own and together they made music that was new and interesting.

Ellington was good at writing music that let musicians improvise and play freely. He also wrote music with strong structures that sounded good together. He knew how each musician played and how they fit together in the band. This helped him create some of the best music in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary talks about Ellington's special sound and how he was a pioneer in jazz. He used the human voice as a musical instrument in many of his songs. This was a new idea at the time. One of his early songs, Creole Love Call, is a good example of this. It is a slow and simple song with six parts:

Part 1: The voice and the woodwind instruments talk to each other. The voice starts with a smooth sound and ends with a rough sound.
Part 2: A trumpet player plays a solo with a lot of feeling and expression.
Part 3: A clarinet player plays a fast and exciting solo with a piano playing a subtle rhythm in the background.
Part 4: The whole band plays together and imitates the first part of the song.
Part 5: The woodwind instruments take the lead and the brass section plays a strong rhythm.
Part 6: The song goes back to the first part, with the voice playing like an instrument.

Ellington also used a special technique called the "growl" in this song. He was good at making his musicians sound good and he liked to experiment with new sounds and ideas.

In another song, Hot and Bothered, Ellington combined his skill at writing music with his ability to create new sounds. He used a trumpet player, Bubber Miley, and a singer, Baby Cox, to make a rich and interesting sound. In another song, It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), Ellington used a trombone player, Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, to introduce the melody in a special way.

Ellington was a master of using the human voice and other instruments to create new and exciting music. He was a true innovator in the world of jazz.

She had a feeling that something was missing. This feeling was not going away. It started when she was 14 years old. Three years later, at 17, she still had this feeling. She decided she wanted to find someone to care about. But she did not feel interested in any boys. Some boys tried to talk to her, but she did not like them. She wondered why this was happening to her. She thought about this problem for a long time. She had some ideas, but they did not make sense.

Her home was usually a peaceful place. Her parents were calm and nice. They did not fight with each other. They rarely argued with her. They argued about her wanting to be free and independent. She was the daughter of calm parents, but she was very outgoing and fun. She was a nice person.

Today was not a calm day. She was looking for something to do when she heard a loud cry from the kitchen. Her mother was lying on the floor. She was hurting and saying "ow" many times. Her daughter rushed to her side. "Mom, what's wrong?" she asked. She saw her mother hurt. "Ow, sweetie, I need you to take me to the hospital," her mother said. Her daughter helped her up and drove her to the hospital.

The hospital smelled bad and was not a nice place. But her daughter was too worried to think about that. She helped her mother into the hospital and called for the doctors. Some people came to help her mother. They rolled her onto a bed and took her to see a doctor. Her daughter sat down and worried.

Her mother fell off a stool when she was getting a vase from a high cabinet.

This study shows that following a "Mediterranean Diet" helps reduce the risk of heart disease and stroke. The diet is known as the aMed diet. It is a special kind of Mediterranean diet. People who follow this diet eat a lot of plant foods, like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes. They also eat more monounsaturated fat and fish. They eat less animal products and saturated fat. A little bit of alcohol is allowed.

Past studies have shown that following the Mediterranean diet can help people live longer and be healthier. They also found that this diet is better than a low-fat diet for losing weight and lowering cholesterol levels.

This study looked at 74,886 women who were 38 to 63 years old. They were all nurses and had never had heart disease or diabetes. The study lasted 20 years. The women answered food questionnaires six times to show what they ate. The researchers used these answers to create a score that showed how well they followed the aMed diet.

The researchers found that women who followed the aMed diet closely had a lower risk of heart disease and stroke. They looked at how many women got heart disease or stroke over 20 years. They found that women who followed the diet closely had a 29% lower risk of heart disease and a 29% lower risk of stroke.

The researchers controlled for other factors that could affect the results, like age, smoking, weight, and exercise. They also looked at how much the women drank and how much aspirin they took. The results showed that following the aMed diet is good for women's heart health.

In 2007, the United States had a big financial problem. Many people were without jobs, and the housing market crashed. Some of America's most important companies went out of business. This big problem continues today. We must ask: how did this happen, and how can we stop it? The answer is simple. The financial crisis was caused by bad and foolish decisions made by politicians. They forced banks and companies to give loans to people who could not pay them back. The banks did not have enough money to cover these loans. They sold these bad loans to other companies and to the public. When people could not pay their loans, the banks lost money and the economy got sick.

This financial problem started in 1999. President Clinton wanted to be elected for a second time. He wanted to be popular. To do this, he made it easier for people to get loans. He wanted more people to buy homes. This made it possible for banks to give loans to people who could not afford them. This was a big mistake.

Steven Holmes, a reporter from the New York Times, wrote about this problem in 1999. He said that Fannie Mae, a company that helps people buy homes, was under pressure to give more loans to people who needed them. He also said that Fannie Mae might have problems if the economy got worse. And that's exactly what happened.

Many factors combined to make the economy worse. Some people got loans that they could not afford to pay back. These loans were called adjustable-rate mortgages. They were like loans that got more expensive over time. People also got loans that were based on bad debts. This made the economy very weak. When the housing market crashed, the banks lost a lot of money. The top five investment banks in the United States had $4.1 trillion dollars of bad loans. This was 30% of the country's wealth. In the end, some of these banks went out of business. The government had to take control of Fannie and Freddie, two big companies that were in trouble.

Exposition: the part of your story where you tell too much.  Dr. Merlin says this can be bad.  It can make readers fall asleep or press the "Back" button.

The rule "Show, don't tell" is well-known.  But Dr. Merlin still tells too much sometimes.  Exposition is like having a devil on your shoulder saying "Tell them now!" 

Exposition means telling what happened.  In movies, this happens when one character tells another a lot of information.  In stories, the writer does the telling.

Here is an example.  In a story, you might be told that a woman met her husband at a certain time and place.  They were married in a big ceremony.  Her husband was killed in front of her.  You would not want this to take a lot of pages.  You would want to know more about the husband and his wife.  You would want to see how they talked and acted to know how much they loved each other.  This would make you feel sad when he dies and care more about the woman.

As a writer, you need to add details.  It is tempting to rush through some parts.  For example, you might want to tell that a new character was in the Air Force and is now the night manager of a gas station.  He was married twice, has no children, and likes to fish.  But this might not be interesting to readers.  They might want to see how he acts and talks, not just what he does.

I watched two news programs from NBC 4 in Columbus, Ohio. The first one was a live broadcast on August 13, 2011. The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who hurt his wife with a knife. The police had arrested him. They showed his picture. I think they spent the right amount of time on this story.

The second story was about a shooting in the Sharon Woods area. A young man named Travis Buyers was shot and is in serious condition. The police have not caught anyone yet. This story was short. I think it might be because the victim was a black man. I have noticed that when a white person is hurt or missing, the news covers it more. But when a minority person is hurt or missing, it gets less attention.

The next story was about a gunshot hole in a helicopter. The police think it happened in a certain area. A small bullet from a rifle hit the helicopter. The police are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for information that helps them catch the person who shot the helicopter.

The next story was about rain and thunderstorms on Saturday afternoon. The weather will be warm, around the mid-eighties. The news wanted to keep you watching.

They also covered a robbery at a store on Clime Road in Columbus. A black man with a hoodie robbed the store. He is about six feet tall and weighs about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they spent too much time saying he was black.

The next story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a big drug dealer. He was caught and will be in prison for twenty-five years. I am not sure why they said "300 months" instead of twenty-five years. They also mentioned he is a Hispanic man, but that is not important to the story.

There is a special bond between brothers. This bond is strong and never breaks. Inside this bond are many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and anger. Brothers know each other very well. They see themselves when they look at their brother. When a situation is very bad, the true nature of this bond appears. This bond can be good or bad. The emotions that come with it can be very costly. Understanding these emotions means dealing with their effects. When you look a brother in the eye and see yourself in them, you see how you really are. Your actions and their results show your true character.

The story "The Scarlet Ibis" shows this idea. Two brothers explore this theme and the strong emotions that come with it. They go on a journey through a beautiful and vivid place. Bitter disappointment and great pride meet in a big moment, and only one brother lives. The story shows this theme through the main character, Doodle, and how he behaves with his brother. It also shows this theme through the narrator, who helps us understand the main character's feelings and how he sees the world.

The main character's actions are all about one feeling: pride. From the start, he wanted a brother to teach him things like running and climbing trees. He wanted a brother to play with and be friends with. But his little brother, Doodle, was sick and could not do these things. This made the main character very sad and angry. He even thought about hurting Doodle. But when Doodle smiled at him, he felt happy and loved him. This shows that his anger was not as strong as he thought. He had a natural love for his brother.

The brain is a very complicated system that processes information. A long time ago, people thought the brain was like a piece of wax. Later, they thought it was like a piece of paper called papyrus. Then, they thought it was like a book. Now, many people think it is like a computer. But the usefulness of these ideas is limited. They can lead to wrong conclusions.

The brain gets information from our senses. Our senses take in things like touch, heat, and light. They change this information into signals that the brain can understand. The brain works with this information in two ways. It looks at the information from the bottom up, and it looks at it from the top down. For example, when you look at a picture of a black box on a white background, the brain first looks at the color, shape, and edges of the box. Then, it uses this information to decide what you are seeing. The top-down process helps you understand what the box is.

The brain also decides which information is important. It uses a filter to decide what to pay attention to. For example, when you look at the grass near your shoes, your brain sees all the blades of grass. But you do not notice them unless you want to. Your brain is very good at focusing on what is important.

The brain stores information in different ways. There is sensory memory, which stores information for a short time. There is also working memory, which stores information for about 20 seconds. And there is long-term memory, which stores information for a long time. To store information, the brain must first change it into a form it can use. This is called encoding. For example, when you hear a word, the brain can encode it in different ways. It can encode the word based on how it looks, how it sounds, or what it means.

The brain is not fully understood. There are many models of how it works. Some models are based on how people remember things. Some are based on computers. And some are based on the brain's physical structure. One model says that the brain is like a network of connected ideas. For example, the idea of a chair might be connected to the idea of a table, which is connected to the idea of wood.

Aldous Huxley writes about a bad future in his book Brave New World. He wants to show the dangers of modern technology and the way society is controlled by the government. In this future, people value being together in a group more than being individual. They are taught from a young age to be happy right now, not to think about the future or past. The people are like pawns in a game. They follow one way of thinking, which is controlled by the World Controller.

Huxley's book is like a warning about the bad things that can happen when we follow a system like capitalism. He uses words from a philosophy called Marxism to show how this system can make people do things they don't want to do. For example, people in the lower classes do not know how the system works. They are brainwashed to want to buy things and be happy, but they do not think about the world around them. The people in charge control the lower classes and make them do what they want.

In Brave New World, the people do not have real relationships with each other. They do not have deep feelings or strong emotions. They only talk about surface things, like how someone looks. This shows that Huxley thinks that modern technology and capitalism can take away our freedom and make us lose our individuality.

The way people in the book accept their place in society is also like what Marx said would happen with capitalism. The lower classes are happy to be lower, and the upper classes do not care about changing the system. This is like a big problem in society. People are not free to think for themselves or feel deep emotions.

Huxley's book is like a warning to us about the dangers of a system that controls people too much. He wants us to think about how we live and what we value.

I am a student at University Park. I have been here for two and a half years. It is difficult for many students to get around campus. We have to walk or bike to class, but our campus is growing. The new buildings and apartments make it hard to find the best way to get to class.

My first year, I lived in East Halls. It was far from the center of campus. I had to walk a lot. It took 25 minutes to walk to class in Willard building. But it was often cold and rainy. The weather made it even harder to walk.

I talked to an old friend. He said he used to like biking to campus. He stopped for a few years, but he thinks biking is the best way to get around. Biking is good for your body and it is fast. I live off campus now. My home is as far from campus as some dorms. I bought a bike and it has been a good decision. I go to Thomas building every day. It takes 5 minutes to ride my bike. But the road I take is not always safe.

Walking is another option, but I am too busy. If I didn’t have a bike, I would have to walk every day. It would take 30-40 minutes. That is over two hours a week. I do not have that much time.

original_texts:
In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

Downwards I stared, mind blankly comprehending the view in front of me.  Unemotionally, silently, with a practiced awareness that studied but refused to relate the object of study to any abstract understanding my mind analyzed the picture before my eyes.  Thoughts slipped into my mind and slipped out again almost faster than they appeared.  So smoothly and so cleanly my consciousness worked that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and liquid experience of what I was looking at. 
Once, on advice from an artist I worked with, I purchased an art instruction book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain.   I had wanted to learn how to draw ever since I was six years old and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to processes the brain uses to interpret lines.  One technique the book teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wishes to study.  Thus transforming an overwhelmingly detailed picture, for instance a bowl of fruit sitting on a table located in a kitchen that is connected to a dining room, into an easily grasped picture, that bowl of fruit sitting on a simple plane.   
At the time, staring down at the bowl in front of me I could not mentally project that artist’s frame.  I was so overwhelmed, so awed that I could only stand and gaze in wonderment.  Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of casting my perspective as worthy of the title Artistic then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown.  
Fingertips alighted on my chosen implement of artistry, muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand passed through space, my mind’s will given shape and form in what could have been the most creative moment of my life.  Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean.  Flakes of matter broke away from the whole and were carried away to nothingness.  Muscles tightening, jerking and spasming a little more quickly and anxious the second time, my hand smacked the handle of the toilet again.  The offensive brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug on the bottom of the toilet.  
Mop gripped loosely in hand, feet set a foot apart, green tie knotted uncomfortably around my throat, I frowned slightly as I stared at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter someone had left as a message for the suckers who cleaned the bathrooms at Rite Aid.  A few flushes more, a few more tranquil introspective moments to myself, then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, gripped the sheet at the end of the toilet paper, and began mummifying itself until it resembled an oven mitt.   Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother going into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey….

Teenagers are dying behind the wheel.  Several factors come together to create this deadly vector of statistics for the youngest American drivers.  The National Institutes of Health explain that one facet of the problem is that the teen brain is literally not ready for the hazards of driving. Simple inexperience also lies at the heart of the problem. This inexperience not only causes more fatal accidents, but also a higher rate of vehicle rollover, speeding, and driving off the road.  
Teens also fare far worse when they travel with their peers—which anyone with an iota of sense knows they do on a regular basis.  The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study that showed the following correlation: between the age of the passenger and the number of traffic accidents occurring.
	California and other states have attempted to increase the safety of teen drivers by requiring temporary provisional licenses that limit the hours that teens may drive and prohibit other minors as passengers.
	But provisional driver’s licenses are, in my opinion, stopgap measures.  The real issue is that—as a group—the youngest drivers are, by all statistical markers, simply not able to adequately handle the risks and responsibilities.  Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver’s license.  USA Today reports that Zuckerman has performed research suggesting a common desire among those under the age of 19-20 to take risks for the sheer thrill of the sensation.  It makes sense then, to delay driving at least until the tendency to thrill-seek has begun to level out.  If we continue to issue driver’s licenses to young teens, we will not only continue to see deadly accidents happening, but the death toll is likely to reach staggering proportions in the next few years.  By 2010, the Baby-Boomer’s babies will be eligible to drive and millions of new teen drivers will ready to hit the road.  
Legislation dealing with this issue would be reasonably straightforward.  Schools could continue to provide driver’s education classes to begin the learning process for future drivers, but no one under the age of 18 could operate a motor vehicle.  A provisional permit could still be issued prior to granting a full driver’s license, and a certain number of practical driver’s training hours would still be required as well.  The specific number of hours required could be based on the number of hours already required by the majority of states (in California, for example, that number is currently 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult.)  Because the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from a cross-section of all states, uniform, national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and I believe effective—means of protecting teens across the nation. 
The legislation I suggest is by no means a novel idea.

In looking through the Library of Congress’s library of early Edison films, I decided to view all of the trick films, of which there were fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films generally take advantage of creative editing to produce illusions.
